<p><span class="postStandFirst">The first true mini flagship has just arrived from Sony, but is the Xperia Z1 Compact worth all the hype?</span></p>
<p>After multiple attempts at creating a desirable mini smartphone from the likes of Samsung and HTC, it looks as if Sony has hit the nail on the head with a device that is as powerful as current flagships, yet small and compact enough to still fit in your pocket.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" alt="" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," width="474" height="640" /></p>
<h2>Design</h2>
<p>Like its big brother the Sony Xperia Z1, the Sony Xperia Z1 Compact features a stunning glass and metal build that oozes quality. With sublime curves and precision engineering the Xperia Z1 Compact feels every bit the flagship handset. Thanks to Sony&rsquo;s ability to construct devices that can withstand day-to-day activities, the Xperia Z1 Compact features the same IP58 certification as the Xperia Z1, meaning the device is capable of being used underwater and is dust resistant as well.</p>
<h2>Display</h2>
<h2><img alt="" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," /></h2>
<p>Unlike the Xperia Z1, the compact features a 720p display, however make no mistake the screen on the device is stunning. At 4.3 inch and flaunting a pixel density of 342ppi, images, text and colours all look pin sharp. Being a Sony device also means that the handset features the company&rsquo;s own screen technologies for image enhancement, so expect to find Triluminos and X-Reality engines to really assist in bringing the screen to life.</p>
<h2>Hardware</h2>
<p>This is an area where the Sony Xperia Z1 Compact really jumps forward compared to the competition. The device features the Snapdragon 800 quad-core processor which features four Krait cores all clocked at 2.26GHz, this is accompanied by 2GB of RAM and an Adreno 330GPU. Simply put, the Xperia Z1 Compact is a real powerhouse device, and has no problem running the latest HD games, multi-tasking or CPU heavy apps. Powering the handset is a 2,300mAh battery, this does offer excellent stamina which coupled with the low-power display and Sony&rsquo;s own Stamina mode software means that the Xperia Z1 Compact can easily last 24 hours even with heavy use.</p>
<h2>Features</h2>
<h2>
<img class="aligncenter" alt="" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," width="640" height="474" /></h2>
<p>Featuring a host of Sony entertainment exclusives, such as Video Unlimited, Walkman and PlayStation Mobile, means that the device is the ultimate on-the-go video, music and games machine.</p>
<h2>Camera</h2>
<p>This is one area where the handset really shines, the Xperia Z1 Compact features a stunning 20.7 megapixel camera complete with LED flash. The camera module itself has the same G Lens technology as the Cybershot compact range of Sony cameras, resulting in some amazing image capture. There is also full HD video recording meaning movies look crisp and detailed. Sony has also packed the device to the rafters with software goodies that all enhance the photographic experience of the phone, such as AR effect, a feature that brings 3D graphics to life in the cameras viewfinder and allow for some unique photo opportunities.</p>
<h2>Software</h2>
<p>Sony has kept things simple with the user interface on the Z1 Compact, with a light customisation of Android 4.3. The software feels clean and responsive but offers some great extras like the Sony exclusive apps and camera modes. The handset will be upgradable to Android 4.4 in the near future and it should have a new fresher looking UI.</p>
<h2 style="text-align: left;">Connectivity</h2>
<h2 style="text-align: left;">
<img class="aligncenter" alt="" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," width="474" height="640" /></h2>
<p>Like the Xperia Z1, the Compact features all the latest in connectivity options. The handset is 4G ready and features Bluetooth 4.0 LE along with Wi-Fi and NFC, the latter being a big part of Sony&rsquo;s eco-system and allowing instant connection to accessories and entertainment systems. The Sony Xperia Z1 Compact also comes with 16GB of internal memory along with the option to expand this by microSD support.</p>
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>There&rsquo;s no doubt about it, Sony has set the bar very high in the mini flagship market. The Xperia Z1 Compact is a marvel and is perfect for those who want a smaller more hand friendly smartphone but don&rsquo;t want to sacrifice power. The device is a true powerhouse with all the extras needed to offer the user everything a flagship smartphone should have, all in all a perfect blend of form and function.</p>
